Author: McGILL
Vol / Page: 320
Edition:
Quote: <i>cross-eyed spieler </i> a glib or crafty fellow, encountered in Frank S. Anthony's <i> Me and Gus,</i> could be originally from Australia, c.1905; from Yiddish `spiel', to play, used generally in English to mean sales patter or swindling, usually at cards.
